        <note>Verse endings denoted by a punctus; The first title page bears the inscription, in large, bold characters: &#1495;&#1500;&#1508;&#1493;&#1503;, and instructions in Judeo-Arabic on the verso. The next title page bears two titles: &#1508;&#1494;&#1488;&#1502;&#1497;&#1503; [&#1500;&#1497;&#1493;]&#1501; &#1506;&#1512;&#1489;&#1492; and &#1508;&#1494;&#1488;&#1502;&#1497;&#1503; &#1500;&#1500;&#1492;&#1493;&#1513;&#1506;&#1504;&#1492;; Fols. 3-4 are fragments from the end of the Hoshanah service of Hoshana Rabba (here: &#1497;&#1493;&#1501; &#1506;&#1512;&#1489;&#1492;), concluding with the headline of the following segment &#1510;&#1500;&#1493;&#1492; &#1513;&#1502;&#1497;&#1504;&#1497; &#1506;&#1510;&#1512;&#1514;. Fols. 5-7 recto include the central Blessing from the 'Amidah for Mussaf of Shemini Atseret; This version assumes the possibility of the Festival occurring on Sabbath, as the day mentioned here is &#1497;&#1493;&#1501; &#1492;&#1502;&#1504;&#1493;&#1495; &#1492;&#1494;&#1492; &#1493;&#1497;&#1493;&#1501; &#1513;&#1502;&#1497;&#1504;&#1497; &#1506;&#1510;&#1512;&#1514; &#1492;&#1494;&#1492; and the Mussaf sacrifice mentioned includes that of Sabbath; Fols. 7 verso-9 contain an expanded version of the daily Blessing on the Torah&#1488;&#1513;&#1512; &#1504;&#1514;&#1503; &#1500;&#1504;&#1493; , the supplement starts&#1488;&#1513;&#1512; &#1489;&#1490;&#1500;&#1500; &#1488;&#1489;&#1493;&#1514; &#1489;&#1504;&#1497;&#1501; &#1490;&#1497;&#1491;&#1500; (Thesaurus of Medieval Hebrew poetry / Israel Davidson. New York, JTS, 1924, 8188&#1488;; Goldschmidt, Mah&#803;azor Sukot, Shemini &#702;atseret v&#803;e-S&#769;imrhat Torah / Ernst Daniel Goldschmidt [ed.]. Jerusalem : Koren, 1981, p. 471), an alphabetic acrostic, for Sim.hat Torah.</note>
